Zoo Animal Classification

The aim is to use Machine Learning Methods to Correctly Classify Animals Based Upon Attributes.

Overview

This data is available from Kaggle, which is published by UCI ML.

There are 2 datasets, namely:

  1. Class dataset - this provides the class name to the class type as well as the list of animals which are corresponding to the class.
##   Class_Number Number_Of_Animal_Species_In_Class Class_Type
## 1            1                                41     Mammal
## 2            2                                20       Bird
##                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Animal_Names
## 1 aardvark, antelope, bear, boar, buffalo, calf, cavy, cheetah, deer, dolphin, elephant, fruitbat, giraffe, girl, goat, gorilla, hamster, hare, leopard, lion, lynx, mink, mole, mongoose, opossum, oryx, platypus, polecat, pony, porpoise, puma, pussycat, raccoon, reindeer, seal, sealion, squirrel, vampire, vole, wallaby, wolf
## 2                                                                                                                                                                                chicken, crow, dove, duck, flamingo, gull, hawk, kiwi, lark, ostrich, parakeet, penguin, pheasant, rhea, skimmer, skua, sparrow, swan, vulture, wren
  1. Zoo - this data consists of the animal names with their features and the class which they are belong. This is what we trying to predict.
##   animal_name hair feathers eggs milk airborne aquatic predator toothed
## 1    aardvark    1        0    0    1        0       0        1       1
## 2    antelope    1        0    0    1        0       0        0       1
##   backbone breathes venomous fins legs tail domestic catsize class_type
## 1        1        1        0    0    4    0        0       1          1
## 2        1        1        0    0    4    1        0       1          1

Note that we can use these 2 datasets to join each other to get full information.

zoo.data <- merge(x = raw.data, y = class.data, by = "class_type", all.x = TRUE)

Supervised learning

Lets try to build supervised machine learning model. In this one, I will use SVM from e1071 library to build the model.

Setting up the training (70%) and testing (30%) datasets.

intraining <- createDataPartition(y=zoo.data$class_type, p=0.7, list=F)
train.batch <- zoo.data[intraining,]
test.batch <- zoo.data[-intraining,]

Before going in the model part, due to the dataset size, I would like to do a quick check on each class sizing.

## ----- Training batch ------
## 
##  1  2  3  4  5  6  7 
## 29 14  4 10  3  6  7
## ----- Testing batch -----
## 
##  1  2  3  4  5  6  7 
## 12  6  1  3  1  2  3

Okay, this looks fine to me. Lets dive to the model set up part.

svm.model <- svm(class_type ~ ., 
                 data=train.batch,
                 kernel = "radial")


summary(svm.model)

test.x <- select(test.batch,
            -class_type,
            -animal_name,
            -class_name)

test.y <- test.batch$class_type

test.pred <- predict(svm.model, test.x)
confusionMatrix(test.pred, test.y)
